The Eccentric Woodland -- Trade Syndic Stability Assessment

The Eccentric Woodland is Midgaard's problem, not ours. It lies
south of their gates, within their claimed jurisdiction, resisting
governance for as long as records exist. The Trade Syndics maintain
a file anyway, because Midgaard's inability to govern its own
backyard has direct implications for Roc Road trade stability.

The Woodland never accepted city law yet never fully escaped city
influence. Patrol reports from every era note the same failures:
path drift, contradictory witness accounts, landmarks that vanish
on follow-up. Midgaard's response has been bureaucratic rather
than practical -- gate records kept clean, interior incidents
classified as variance events, plausible governance at the edge.

The Syndics recognize this as performative jurisdiction: the
appearance of control substituting for actual control. Sigils
repainted, reports filed, while inside four forces contest ground
no city office will absorb. Path Wardens selling navigation.
Ritual Houses legitimating rank through ceremony. Predator
Bands mimicking ritual forms. Survivor Clusters bartering
in burrows.

Wall Command asks the practical question: if Midgaard cannot
stabilize a forest this close to its own southern gate, what
happens when their Roc Road commitments demand the same patrols?
The Northern Covenant, the Lantern Road, the Forest patrols -- all
depend on Midgaard fielding wardens. Every warden watching the
Woodland is a warden not watching the road.

Kiess convoy marshals report Midgaard's eastern road discipline has
been slowly degrading for three seasons. The Syndics cannot prove
causation, but the correlation between southern distraction and
eastern neglect is noted in every quarterly assessment.

The deeper lesson is institutional. Midgaard's core doctrine is
order as infrastructure. The Eccentric Woodland proves that
doctrine has limits. When terrain resists standardization, Midgaard
reclassifies the anomaly rather than adapting the method. Kiess was
founded on the opposite principle: adapt the method to the terrain,
or the terrain will adapt you.

The Woodland persists as everyone's blind spot. The Prism Archive
records it as what happens when governance reaches its boundary
and refuses to acknowledge the edge.
